no_docstring:\n   605\t            warnings.warn("The \'no_docstring\' argument to %s.add_content() is deprecated."\n   606\t                          % self.__class__.__name__,\n   607\t                          RemovedInSphinx50Warning, stacklevel=2)\n   608\t\n   609\t        # set sourcename and add content from attribute documentation\n   610\t        sourcename = self.get_sourcename()\n   611\t        if self.analyzer:\n   612\t            attr_docs = self.analyzer.find_attr_docs()\n   613\t            if self.objpath:\n   614\t                key = (\'.\'.join(self.objpath[:-1]), self.objpath[-1])\n   615\t                if key in attr_docs:\n   616\t                    no_docstring = True\n   617\t                    # make a copy of docstring for attributes to avoid cache\n   618\t                    # the change of autodoc-process-docstring event.\n   619\t                    docstrings = [list(attr_docs[key])]\n   620\t\n   621\t                    for i, line in enumerate(self.process_doc(docstrings)):\n   622\t                        self.add_line(line, sourcename, i)\n   623\t\n   624\t        # add content from docstrings\n   625\t        if not no_docstring:\n   626\t            docstrings = self.get_doc()\n   627\t            if docstrings is None:\n   628\t                # Do not call autodoc-process-docstring on get_doc() returns None.\n   629\t                pass\n   630\t            else:\n   631\t                if not docstrings:\n   632\t                    # append at least a dummy docstring, so that the event\n   633\t                    # autodoc-process-docstring is fired and can add some\n   634\t                    # content if desired\n   635\t                    docstrings.append([])\n   636\t                for i, line in enumerate(self.process_doc(docstrings)):\n   637\t                    self.add_line(line, sourcename, i)\n   638\t\n   639\t        # add additional content (e.g. from document), if present\n   640\t        if more_content:\n   641\t            for line, src in zip(more_content.data, more_content.items):\n   642\t                self.add_line(line, src[0], src[1])\n   643\t\n   644\t    def get_object_members(self, want_all: bool) -> Tuple[bool, ObjectMembers]:\n   645\t        """Return `(members_check_module, members)` where `members` is a\n   646\t        list of `(membername, member)` pairs of the members of *self.object*.\n   647\t\n   648\t        If *want_all* is True, return all members.  Else, only return those\n   649\t        members given by *self.options.members* (which may also be None).\n   650\t        """\n   651\t        warnings.warn(\'The implementation of Documenter.get_object_members() will be \'\n   652\t                      \'removed from Sphinx-6.0.\', RemovedInSphinx60Warning)\n   653\t        members = get_object_members(self.object, self.objpath, self.get_attr, self.analyzer)\n   654\t        if not want_all:\n   655\t            if not self.options.members:\n   656\t                return False, []  # type: ignore\n   657\t            # specific members given\n   658\t            selected = []\n   659\t            for name in self.options.members:  # type: str\n   660\t                if name in members:\n   661\t                    selected.append((name, members[name].value))\n   662\t                else:\n   663\t                    logger.warning(__(\'missing attribute %s in object %s\') %\n   664\t                                   (name, self.fullname), type=\'autodoc\')\n   665\t            return False, selected\n   666\t        elif self.options.inherited_members:\n   667\t            return False, [(m.name, m.value) for m in members.values()]\n   668\t        else:\n   669\t            return False, [(m.name, m.value) for m in members.values()\n   670\t                           if m.directly_defined]\n   671\t\n   672\t    def filter_members(self, members: ObjectMembers, want_all: bool\n   673\t                       ) -> List[Tuple[str, Any, bool]]:\n   674\t        """Filter the given member list.\n   675\t\n   676\t        Members are skipped if\n   677\t\n   678\t        - they are private (except if given explicitly or the private-members\n   679\t          option is set)\n   680\t        - they are special methods (except if given explicitly or the\n   681\t          special-members option is set)\n   682\t        - they are undocumented (except if the undoc-members option is set)\n   683\t\n   684\t        The user can override the skipping decision by connecting to the\n   685\t        ``autodoc-skip-member`` event.\n   686\t        """\n   687\t        def is_filtered_inherited_member(name: str, obj: Any) -> bool:\n   688\t            if inspect.isclass(self.object):\n   689\t                for cls in self.object.__mro__:\n   690\t                    if cls.__name__ == self.options.inherited_members and cls != self.object:\n   691\t                        # given member is a member of specified *super class*\n   692\t                        return True\n   693\t                    elif name in cls.__dict__:\n   694\t                        return False\n   695\t                    elif name in self.get_attr(cls, \'__annotations__\', {}):\n   696\t                        return False\n   697\t                    elif isinstance(obj, ObjectMember) and obj.class_ is cls:\n   698\t                        return False\n   699\t\n   700\t            return False\n   701\t\n   702\t        ret = []\n   703\t\n   704\t        # search for members in source code too\n   705\t        namespace = \'.\'.join(self.objpath)  # will be empty for modules\n   706\t\n   707\t        if self.analyzer:\n   708\t            attr_docs = self.analyzer.find_attr_docs()\n   709\t        else:\n   710\t            attr_docs = {}\n   711\t\n   712\t        # process members and determine which to skip\n   713\t        for obj in members:\n   714\t            membername, member = obj\n   715\t            # if isattr is True, the member is documented as an attribute\n   716\t            if member is INSTANCEATTR:\n   717\t                isattr = True\n   718\t            elif (namespace, membername) in attr_docs:\n   719\t                isattr = True\n   720\t            else:\n   721\t                isattr = False\n   722\t\n   723\t            doc = getdoc(member, self.get_attr, self.config.autodoc_inherit_docstrings,\n   724\t                         self.object, membername)\n   725\t            if not isinstance(doc, str):\n   726\t                # Ignore non-string __doc__\n   727\t                doc = None\n   728\t\n   729\t            # if the member __doc__ is the same as self\'s __doc__, it\'s just\n   730\t            # inherited and therefore not the member\'s doc\n   731\t            cls = self.get_attr(member, \'__class__\', None)\n   732\t            if cls:\n   733\t                cls_doc = self.get_attr(cls, \'__doc__\', None)\n   734\t                if cls_doc == doc:\n   735\t                    doc = None\n   736\t\n   737\t            if isinstance(obj, ObjectMember) and obj.docstring:\n   738\t                # hack for ClassDocumenter to inject docstring via ObjectMember\n   739\t                doc = obj.docstring\n   740\t\n   741\t            doc, metadata = separate_metadata(doc)\n   742\t            has_doc = bool(doc)\n   743\t\n   744\t            if \'private\' in metadata:\n   745\t                # consider a member private if docstring has "private" metadata\n   746\t                isprivate = True\n   747\t            elif \'public\' in metadata:\n   748\t                # consider a member public if docstring has "public" metadata\n   749\t                isprivate = False\n   750\t            else:\n   751\t                isprivate = membername.startswith(\'_\')\n   752\t\n   753\t            keep = False\n   754\t            if ismock(member):\n   755\t                # mocked module or object\n   756\t                pass\n   757\t            elif self.options.exclude_members and membername in self.options.exclude_members:\n   758\t                # remove members given by exclude-members\n   759\t                keep = False\n   760\t            elif want_all and special_member_re.match(membername):\n   761\t                # special __methods__\n   762\t                if self.options.special_members and membername in self.options.special_members:\n   763\t                    if membername == \'__doc__\':\n   764\t                        keep = False\n   765\t                    elif is_filtered_inherited_member(membername, obj):\n   766\t                        keep = False\n   767\t                    else:\n   768\t                        keep = has_doc or self.options.undoc_members\n   769\t                else:\n   770\t                    keep = False\n   771\t            elif (namespace, membername) in attr_docs:\n   772\t                if want_all and isprivate:\n   773\t                    if self.options.private_members is None:\n   774\t                        keep = False\n   775\t                    else:\n   776\t                        keep = membername in self.options.private_members\n   777\t                else:\n   778\t                    # keep documented attributes\n   779\t                    keep = True\n   780\t            elif want_all and isprivate:\n   781\t                if has_doc or self.options.undoc_members:\n   782\t                    if self.options.private_members is None:\n   783\t                        keep = False\n   784\t                    elif is_filtered_inherited_member(membername, obj):\n   785\t                        keep = False\n   786\t                    else:\n   787\t                        keep = membername in self.options.private_members\n   788\t                else:\n   789\t                    keep = False\n   790\t            else:\n   791\t                if (self.options.members is ALL and\n   792\t                        is_filtered_inherited_member(membername, obj)):\n   793\t                    keep = False\n   794\t                else:\n   795\t                    # ignore undocumented members if :undoc-members: is not given\n   796\t                    keep = has_doc or self.options.undoc_members\n   797\t\n   798\t            if isinstance(obj, ObjectMember) and obj.skipped:\n   799\t                # forcedly skipped member (ex. a module attribute not defined in __all__)\n   800\t                keep = False\n   801\t\n   802\t            # give the user a chance to decide whether this member\n   803\t            # should be skipped\n   804\t            if self.env.app:\n   805\t                # let extensions preprocess docstrings\n   806\t                try:\n   807\t                    skip_user = self.env.app.emit_firstresult(\n   808\t                        \'autodoc-skip-member\', self.objtype, membername, member,\n   809\t                        not keep, self.options)\n   810\t                    if skip_user is not None:\n   811\t                        keep = not skip_user\n   812\t                except Exception as exc:\n   813\t                    logger.warning(__(\'autodoc: failed to determine %r to be documented, \'\n   814\t                                      \'the following exception was raised:\\n%s\'),\n   815\t                                   member, exc, type=\'autodoc\')\n   816\t                    keep = False\n   817\t\n   818\t            if keep:\n   819\t                ret.append((membername, member, isattr))\n   820\t\n   821\t        return ret\n   822\t\n   823\t    def document_members(self, all_members: bool = False) -> None:\n   824\t        """Generate reST for member documentation.\n   825\t\n   826\t        If *all_members* is True, document all members, else those given by\n   827\t        *self.options.members*.\n   828\t        """\n   829\t        # set current namespace for finding members\n   830\t        self.env.temp_data[\'autodoc:module\'] = self.modname\n   831\t        if self.objpath:\n   832\t            self.env.temp_data[\'autodoc:class\'] = self.objpath[0]\n   833\t\n   834\t        want_all = (all_members or\n   835\t                    self.options.inherited_members or\n   836\t                    self.options.members is ALL)\n   837\t        # find out which members are documentable\n   838\t        members_check_module, members = self.get_object_members(want_all)\n   839\t\n   840\t        # document non-skipped members\n   841\t        memberdocumenters: List[Tuple[Documenter, bool]] = []\n   842\t        for (mname, member, isattr) in self.filter_members(members, want_all):\n   843\t            classes = [cls for cls in self.documenters.values()\n   844\t                       if cls.can_document_member(member, mname, isattr, self)]\n   845\t            if not classes:\n   846\t                # don\'t know how to document this member\n   847\t                continue\n   848\t            # prefer the documenter with the highest priority\n   849\t            classes.sort(key=lambda cls: cls.priority)\n   850\t            # give explicitly separated module name, so that members\n   851\t            # of inner classes can be documented\n   852\t            full_mname = self.modname + \'::\' + \'.\'.join(self.objpath + [mname])\n   853\t            documenter = classes[-1](self.directive, full_mname, self.indent)\n   854\t            memberdocumenters.append((documenter, isattr))\n   855\t\n   856\t        member_order = self.options.member_order or self.config.autodoc_member_order\n   857\t        memberdocumenters = self.sort_members(memberdocumenters, member_order)\n   858\t\n   859\t        for documenter, isattr in memberdocumenters:\n   860\t            documenter.generate(\n   861\t                all_members=True, real_modname=self.real_modname,\n   862\t                check_module=members_check_module and not isattr)\n   863\t\n   864\t        # reset current objects\n   865\t        self.env.temp_data[\'autodoc:module\'] = None\n   866\t        self.env.temp_data[\'autodoc:class\'] = None\n   867\t\n   868\t    def sort_members(self, documenters: List[Tuple["Documenter", bool]],\n   869\t                     order: str) -> List[Tuple["Documenter", bool]]:\n   870\t        """Sort the given member list."""\n   871\t        if order == \'groupwise\':\n   872\t            # sort by group; alphabetically within groups\n   873\t            documenters.sort(key=lambda e: (e[0].member_order, e[0].name))\n   874\t        elif order == \'bysource\':\n   875\t            if self.analyzer:\n   876\t                # sort by source order, by virtue of the module analyzer\n   877\t                tagorder = self.analyzer.tagorder\n   878\t\n   879\t                def keyfunc(entry: Tuple[Documenter, bool]) -> int:\n   880\t                    fullname = entry[0].name.split(\'::\')[1]\n   881\t                    return tagorder.get(fullname, len(tagorder))\n   882\t                documenters.sort(key=keyfunc)\n   883\t            else:\n   884\t                # Assume that member discovery order matches source order.\n   885\t                # This is a reasonable assumption in Python 3.6 and up, where\n   886\t                # module.__dict__ is insertion-ordered.\n   887\t                pass\n   888\t        else:  # alphabetical\n   889\t            documenters.sort(key=lambda e: e[0].name)\n   890\t\n   891\t        return documenters\n   892\t\n   893\t    def generate(self, more_content: Optional[StringList] = None, real_modname: str = None,\n   894\t                 check_module: bool = False, all_members: bool = False) -> None:\n   895\t        """Generate reST for the object given by *self.name*, and possibly for\n   896\t        its members.\n   897\t\n   898\t        If *more_content* is given, include that content. If *real_modname* is\n   899\t        given, use that module name to find attribute docs. If *check_module* is\n   900\t        True, only generate if the object is defined in the module name it is\n   901\t        imported from. If *all_members* is True, document all members.\n   902\t        """\n   903\t        if not self.parse_name():\n   904\t            # need a module to import\n   905\t            logger.warning(\n   906\t                __(\'don\\\'t know which module to import for autodocumenting \'\n   907\t                   \'%r (try placing a "module" or "currentmodule" directive \'\n   908\t                   \'in the document, or giving an explicit module name)\') %\n   909\t                self.name, type=\'autodoc\')\n   910\t            return\n   911\t\n   912\t        # now, import the module and get object to document\n   913\t        if not self.import_object():\n   914\t            return\n   915\t\n   916\t        # If there is no real module defined, figure out which to use.\n   917\t        # The real module is used in the module analyzer to look up the module\n   918\t        # where the attribute documentation would actually be found in.\n   919\t        # This is used for situations where you have a module that collects the\n   920\t        # functions and classes of internal submodules.\n   921\t        guess_modname = self.get_real_modname()\n   922\t        self.real_modname: str = real_modname or guess_modname\n   923\t\n   924\t        # try to also get a source code analyzer for attribute docs\n   925\t        try:\n   926\t            self.analyzer = ModuleAnalyzer.for_module(self.real_modname)\n   927\t            # parse right now, to get PycodeErrors on parsing (results will\n   928\t            # be cached anyway)\n   929\t            self.analyzer.find_attr_docs()\n   930\t        except PycodeError as exc:\n   931\t            logger.debug(\'[autodoc] module analyzer failed: %s\', exc)\n   932\t            # no source file -- e.g. for builtin and C modules\n   933\t            self.analyzer = None\n   934\t            # at least add the module.__file__ as a dependency\n   935\t            if hasattr(self.module, \'__file__\') and self.module.__file__:\n   936\t                self.directive.record_dependencies.add(self.module.__file__)\n   937\t        else:\n   938\t            self.directive.record_dependencies.add(self.analyzer.srcname)\n   939\t\n   940\t        if self.real_modname != guess_modname:\n   941\t            # Add module to dependency list if target object is defined in other module.\n   942\t            try:\n   943\t                analyzer = ModuleAnalyzer.for_module(guess_modname)\n   944\t                self.directive.record_dependencies.add(analyzer.srcname)\n   945\t            except PycodeError:\n   946\t                pass\n   947\t\n   948\t        docstrings: List[str] = sum(self.get_doc() or [], [])\n   949\t        if ismock(self.object) and not docstrings:\n   950\t            logger.warning(__(\'A mocked object is detected: %r\'),\n   951\t                           self.name, type=\'autodoc\')\n   952\t\n   953\t        # check __module__ of object (for members not given explicitly)\n   954\t        if check_module:\n   955\t            if not self.check_module():\n   956\t                return\n   957\t\n   958\t        sourcename = self.get_sourcename()\n   959\t\n   960\t        # make sure that the result starts with an empty line.  This is\n   961\t        # necessary for some situations where another directive preprocesses\n   962\t        # reST and no starting newline is present\n   963\t        self.add_line(\'\', sourcename)\n   964\t\n   965\t        # format the object\'s signature, if any\n   966\t        try:\n   967\t            sig = self.format_signature()\n   968\t        except Exception as exc:\n   969\t            logger.warning(__(\'error while formatting signature for %s: %s\'),\n   970\t                           self.fullname, exc, type=\'autodoc\')\n   971\t            return\n   972\t\n   973\t        # generate the directive header and options, if applicable\n   974\t        self.add_directive_header(sig)\n   975\t        self.add_line(\'\', sourcename)\n   976\t\n   977\t        # e.g. the module directive doesn\'t have content\n   978\t        self.indent += self.content_indent\n   979\t\n   980\t        # add all content (from docstrings, attribute docs etc.)\n   981\t        self.add_content(more_content)\n   982\t\n   983\t        # document members, if possible\n   984\t        self.document_members(all_members)\n   985\t\n   986\t\n   987\tclass ModuleDocumenter(Documenter):\n   988\t    """\n   989\t    Specialized Documenter subclass for modules.\n   990\t    """\n   991\t    objtype = \'module\'\n   992\t    content_indent = \'\'\n   993\t    titles_allowed = True\n   994\t\n   995\t    option_spec: OptionSpec = {\n   996\t        \'members\': members_option, \'undoc-members\': bool_option,\n   997\t        \'noindex\': bool_option, 1000\t        \'member-order\': member_order_option, \'exclude-members\': exclude_members_option,\n  1001\t        \'private-members\': members_option, \'special-members\': members_option,\n  1002\t        \'imported-members\': bool_option, \'ignore-module-all\': bool_option\n  1003\t    }\n  1004\t\n  1005\t    def __init__(self, *args: Any) -> None:\n  1006\t        super().__init__(*args)\n  1007\t        merge_members_option(self.options)\n  1008\t        self.__all__: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None\n  1009\t\n  1010\t    @classmethod\n  1011\t    def can_document_member(cls, member: Any, membername: str, isattr: bool, parent: Any\n  1012\t                            ) -> bool:\n  1013\t        # don\'t document submodules automatically\n  1014\t        return False\n  1015\t\n  1016\t    def resolve_name(self, modname: str, parents: Any, path: str, base: Any\n  1017\t                     ) -> Tuple[str, List[str]]:\n  1018\t        if modname is not None:\n  1019\t            logger.warning(__(\'"::" in automodule name doesn\\\'t make sense\'),\n  1020\t                           type=\'autodoc\')\n  1021\t        return (path or \'\') + base, []\n  1022\t\n  1023\t    def import_object(self, raiseerror: bool = False) -> bool:\n  1032\t        ret = super().import_object(raiseerror)\n  1033\t\n  1034\t        try:\n  1035\t            if not self.options.ignore_module_all:\n  1036\t                self.__all__ = inspect.getall(self.object)\n  1037\t        except ValueError as exc:\n  1038\t            # invalid __all__ found.\n  1039\t get_module_members(self) -> Dict[str, ObjectMember]:\n  1059\t        """Get members of target module."""\n  1060\t        if self.analyzer:\n  1061\t            attr_docs = self.analyzer.attr_docs\n  1062\t        else:\n  1063\t            attr_docs = {}\n  1064\t\n  1065\t        members: Dict[str, ObjectMember] = {}\n  1066\t        for name in dir(self.object):\n  1067\t            try:\n  1068\t                value = safe_getattr(self.object, name, None)\n  1069\t                if ismock(value):\n  1070\t                    value = undecorate(value)\n  1071\t                docstring   continue\n  1075\t\n  1076\t        # annotation only member (ex. attr: int)\n  1077\t        for name in inspect.getannotations(self.object):\n  1078\t            if name not in members:\n  1079\t                docstring = attr_docs.get((\'\', name), [])\n  1080\t                members[name] = ObjectMember(name, INSTANCEATTR,\n  1081\t                                             docstring="\\n".join(docstring))\n  1082\t\n  1083\t        return members\n  1084\t\n  1085\t    def get_object_members(self, want_all: bool) -> Tuple[bool, ObjectMembers]:\n  1086\t        members = self.get_module_members()\n  1087\t        if want_all:\n  1088\t            if self.__all__ is None:\n  1089\t                # for implicit module members, check __module__ to avoid\n  1090\t                # documenting imported objects\n  1091\t                return True, list(members.values())\n  1092\t            else:\n  1093\t                for member in members.values():\n  1094\t                    if member.__name__ not in self.__all__:\n  1095\t                        member.skipped = True\n  1096\t\n  1097\t                return False, list(members.values())\n  1098\t     # the feature is enabled\n  1253\t            result = self._find_signature()\n  1254\t            if result is not None:\n  1255\t                self.args, self.retann = result\n  1256\t python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p=Path('sympy/geometry/point.py')
s=p.read_text()
old='        return Point(coords, evaluate=False)\n'
if old in s and 'def __rmul__(' not in s:
    insert = (
        "        return Point(coords, evaluate=False)\n\n"
        "    def __rmul__(self, factor):\n"
        "        \"\"\"Right-hand multiplication: allow number * Point to work the same\n"
        "        as Point * number.\"\"\"\n"
        "        return self.__mul__(factor)\n"
    )
    s = s.replace(old, insert)
    p.write_text(s)
    print('patched')
else:
    print('no change needed or pattern not found')
PY

user response: I searched the codebase for references to SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS and inspected the relevant implementation.

Findings
- django/conf/global_settings.py defines:
  - SECRET_KEY (line ~264)
  - SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS = [] (line ~268)
  - The comment only says: "List of secret keys used to verify the validity of signatures. This allows secret key rotation." â€” no longer explanation about ordering/usage.

- django/utils/crypto.py implements salted_hmac(key_salt, value, secret=None, *, algorithm="sha1"):
  - If secret is None, it uses settings.SECRET_KEY (line 26â€“27).
  - There is no logic in salted_hmac that uses SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS.

- I also searched tests referencing SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS (tests/auth_tests/test_tokens.py) â€” the tests assume fallback support exists in appropriate signing/token validation code.

Conclusion
- The salted_hmac helper uses only settings.SECRET_KEY when secret is not provided.
- If other parts of Django that validate signatures/tokens do not explicitly pass a different secret value when verifying, they will only use settings.SECRET_KEY (the current key). That means setting SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS by itself will not make those code paths automatically attempt verification with previous keys unless those code paths are explicitly implemented to do so.
- Therefore the documentation text you quoted (which instructs to put previous keys in SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS and expect sessions/password-reset tokens to keep working) is misleading unless the specific signing/verification code uses SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS. The implementation shows salted_hmac doesn't consult fallbacks, so some token/session verification code would need to explicitly try fallbacks to actually preserve validity across rotation.

Next steps / Patch
- The repository does not currently contain a detailed docstring describing the rotation procedure with SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS (only the brief global_settings comment), so the right fix is to update the documentation to clarify behavior: explain that salted_hmac uses SECRET_KEY by default, and that callers that want fallback support must attempt verification using SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS themselves (or the framework must be updated to try fallbacks in the relevant verification functions).
- If you want, I can prepare a patch that updates the comment in django/conf/global_settings.py to clarify the semantics of SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS (i.e., it's only a store of additional keys; code that verifies signatures must explicitly try them), and optionally add tests or change higher-level verification functions to automatically try fallbacks. Tell me which you'd prefer:
  - (A) Add clarifying comment in global_settings.py (minimal documentation fix).
  - (B) Implement fallback checking in relevant verification functions (larger change â€” specify which: auth token validation? signing functions? sessions?) and tests.
  - (C) Both (A) and (B).

If you want the minimal documentation patch (A), I'll produce and return the patch. Which option do you want?

user response: I'll modify django/db/migrations/writer.py to ensure plain "import ..." statements are placed before "from ... import ..." lines when formatting migration imports.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('django/db/migrations/writer.py')
s = p.read_text()
old = "        # Sort imports by the package / module to be imported (the part after\n        # \"from\" in \"from ... import ...\" or after \"import\" in \"import ...\").\n        sorted_imports = sorted(imports, key=lambda i: i.split()[1])\n        items[\"imports\"] = \"\\n\".join(sorted_imports) + \"\\n\" if imports else \"\""
if old in s:
    new = "        # Place plain module imports before \"from ... import ...\" lines, and\n        # sort within those groups by the package/module name (the part after\n        # \"from\" in \"from ... import ...\" or after \"import\" in \"import ...\").\n        sorted_imports = sorted(\n            imports,\n            key=lambda i: (0 if i.startswith(\"import \") else 1, i.split()[1]),\n        )\n        items[\"imports\"] = \"\\n\".join(sorted_imports) + \"\\n\" if imports else \"\""
    s = s.replace(old, new)
    p.write_text(s)
    print("patched")
else:
    # Fallback: try to replace the one-line sorted call if formatting differs
    s2 = s.replace('sorted(imports, key=lambda i: i.split()[1])', 'sorted(\\n            imports,\\n            key=lambda i: (0 if i.startswith(\"import \") else 1, i.split()[1]),\\n        )')
    if s2 != s:
        p.write_text(s2)
        print("patched (alt)")
    else:
        print("pattern not found")

user response: I added a __rmul__ method to sympy.geometry.point.Point so numeric * Point will delegate to Point.__mul__, preventing creation of a Mul containing a Point (which causes errors when adding Points).

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
finish
----ARG----
result
----VALUE----
Add __rmul__ to Point so number * Point delegates to Point.__mul__

This patch adds a right-hand multiplication method to sympy.geometry.point.Point:

    def __rmul__(self, factor):
        """Right-hand multiplication: allow number * Point to work the same
        as Point * number."""
        return self.__mul__(factor)

This prevents expressions like 2.0 * Point(1,1) from producing a Mul containing a Point (e.g. Mul(2.0, Point2D(1,1))), which later caused TypeError in Point.__add__ when Point() tried to interpret the Mul as coordinates.

File modified:
- sympy/geometry/point.py
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----
user response: your_thoughts_here
I'll update django/core/handlers/base.py to avoid mutating the "handler" variable before a middleware factory successfully constructs its instance. This prevents the handler from being "poisoned" when a middleware factory raises MiddlewareNotUsed. I'll change the temporary adaptation to use a local variable adapted_handler and only assign to handler after the middleware instance is created successfully.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('django/core/handlers/base.py')
s = p.read_text()
old = (
    "                # Adapt handler, if needed.\n"
    "                handler = self.adapt_method_mode(\n"
    "                    middleware_is_async, handler, handler_is_async,\n"
    "                    debug=settings.DEBUG, name='middleware %s' % middleware_path,\n"
    "                )\n"
    "                mw_instance = middleware(handler)\n"
)
new = (
    "                # Adapt handler, if needed. Use a local adapted_handler so that\n"
    "                # if the middleware factory raises MiddlewareNotUsed we don't\n"
    "                # mutate the current handler and its async/sync mode.\n"
    "                adapted_handler = self.adapt_method_mode(\n"
    "                    middleware_is_async, handler, handler_is_async,\n"
    "                    debug=settings.DEBUG, name='middleware %s' % middleware_path,\n"
    "                )\n"
    "                mw_instance = middleware(adapted_handler)\n"
)
if old in s:
    s = s.replace(old, new)
    p.write_text(s)
    print('patched')
else:
    print('pattern not found')
PY
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

I'll apply the change, run a small reproduction script to validate, and then return the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path("sklearn/compose/_column_transformer.py")
s = p.read_text()
old_marker = "def set_output(self, *, transform=None):"
if old_marker not in s:
    raise SystemExit("set_output not found")
start = s.index(old_marker)
# find the end of method by locating the 'def get_params' that follows
end_marker = "\n    def get_params(self, deep=True):"
end = s.index(end_marker, start)
old_method = s[start:end]
# New method implementation
new_method = '''def set_output(self, *, transform=None):
        """Set the output container when `"transform"` and `"fit_transform"` are called.

        Calling `set_output` will set the output of all estimators in `transformers`
        and `transformers_`.

        Parameters
        ----------
        transform : {"default", "pandas"}, default=None
            Configure output of `transform` and `fit_transform`.

            - `"default"`: Default output format of a transformer
            - `"pandas"`: DataFrame output
            - `None`: Transform configuration is unchanged

        Returns
        -------
        self : estimator instance
            Estimator instance.
        """
        super().set_output(transform=transform)

        # Collect transformers from both the parameter list (self.transformers)
        # and the fitted list (self.transformers_) if present. Filter out the
        # 'passthrough' and 'drop' specifiers which are not estimators.
        trans_list = [
            trans
            for _, trans, _ in chain(
                self.transformers, getattr(self, "transformers_", [])
            )
            if trans not in {"passthrough", "drop"}
        ]

        # Also ensure we include the remainder estimator (the parameter),
        # if it is an estimator (not 'passthrough' or 'drop') and not already
        # present in the collected transformers. This covers the common case
        # where set_output is called before fitting: the remainder estimator
        # lives in self.remainder and is not part of self.transformers.
        if hasattr(self, "remainder"):
            rem = self.remainder
            if rem not in ("passthrough", "drop") and rem not in trans_list:
                trans_list.append(rem)

        for trans in trans_list:
            _safe_set_output(trans, transform=transform)

        return self
'''
# Replace
new_s = s[:start] + new_method + s[end:]
p.write_text(new_s)
print("updated", p)

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----

----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p=Path("django/views/generic/base.py")
s=p.read_text()
old="""    def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):
        kwargs.setdefault('view', self)
        if self.extra_context is not None:
            kwargs.update(self.extra_context)
        return kwargs
"""
if old not in s:
    print("Original block not found; aborting")
    raise SystemExit(1)
new="""    def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):
        \"\"\"
        Build the context dictionary to be used in template rendering.
\n        Historically URL kwargs passed through TemplateView.get() were plain
        values. In Django 3.1 they are wrapped in SimpleLazyObject instances
        (so that accessing them from a template emits a deprecation warning).
        That wrapping caused surprising errors when user code in
        get_context_data() attempted to use those kwargs directly (for
        example, passing a SimpleLazyObject into a queryset filter raises
        \"unsupported type\").
\n        To preserve the expectation that get_context_data() receives the
        actual URL kwarg values, unwrap any SimpleLazyObject instances here
        before returning the context.
        \"\"\"
        # Force evaluation of any SimpleLazyObject values so callers of
        # get_context_data() receive concrete values (not proxy objects).
        for key, value in list(kwargs.items()):
            if isinstance(value, SimpleLazyObject):
                # Accessing any attribute on the proxy forces evaluation.
                # We use getattr(..., '__class__') which triggers evaluation
                # without assuming a specific representation.
                try:
                    getattr(value, '__class__')
                except Exception:
                    # If evaluation raises, leave the proxy as-is so that
                    # the original error is propagated where appropriate.
                    continue
                # Replace the SimpleLazyObject in kwargs with its wrapped value.
                try:
                    # _wrapped is a private attribute that will be set once the
                    # proxy has been evaluated.
                    wrapped = getattr(value, '_wrapped', value)
                except Exception:
                    wrapped = value
                kwargs[key] = wrapped
\n        kwargs.setdefault('view', self)
        if self.extra_context is not None:
            kwargs.update(self.extra_context)
        return kwargs
"""
s=s.replace(old,new,1)
p.write_text(s)
print("Replaced block successfully")

+        # Prepare to run psql. Use PGPASSWORD in a copied environment to avoid
+        # creating a temporary .pgpass file. subprocess.run allows passing a
+        # custom environment dict. Keep SIGINT handling similar to previous
+        # behavior so keyboard interrupts can abort queries.
+        sigint_handler = signal.getsignal(signal.SIGINT)
+        try:
+            env = None
+            if passwd:
+                # Copy the current environment and set PGPASSWORD for the child.
+                env = os.environ.copy()
+                env['PGPASSWORD'] = passwd
+            # Allow SIGINT to pass to psql to abort queries.
+            signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, signal.SIG_IGN)
+            # Use subprocess.run (available since Python 3.5) and raise on error.
+            subprocess.run(args, env=env, check=True)
+        finally:
+            # Restore the original SIGINT handler.
+            signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, sigint_handler)

user response: I will modify django/db/models/deletion.py so that in the optimized single-instance fast-delete path the instance's primary key attribute is cleared (set to None) after the database delete. I'll update the file and return the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
cat > django/db/models/deletion.py <<'PY'
from collections import Counter
from operator import attrgetter

from django.db import IntegrityError, connections, transaction
from django.db.models import signals, sql


class ProtectedError(IntegrityError):
    def __init__(self, msg, protected_objects):
        self.protected_objects = protected_objects
        super().__init__(msg, protected_objects)


def CASCADE(collector, field, sub_objs, using):
    collector.collect(sub_objs, source=field.remote_field.model,
                      source_attr=field.name, nullable=field.null)
    if field.null and not connections[using].features.can_defer_constraint_checks:
        collector.add_field_update(field, None, sub_objs)


def PROTECT(collector, field, sub_objs, using):
    raise ProtectedError(
        "Cannot delete some instances of model '%s' because they are "
        "referenced through a protected foreign key: '%s.%s'" % (
            field.remote_field.model.__name__, sub_objs[0].__class__.__name__, field.name
        ),
        sub_objs
    )


def SET(value):
    if callable(value):
        def set_on_delete(collector, field, sub_objs, using):
            collector.add_field_update(field, value(), sub_objs)
    else:
        def set_on_delete(collector, field, sub_objs, using):
            collector.add_field_update(field, value, sub_objs)
    set_on_delete.deconstruct = lambda: ('django.db.models.SET', (value,), {})
    return set_on_delete


def SET_NULL(collector, field, sub_objs, using):
    collector.add_field_update(field, None, sub_objs)


def SET_DEFAULT(collector, field, sub_objs, using):
    collector.add_field_update(field, field.get_default(), sub_objs)


def DO_NOTHING(collector, field, sub_objs, using):
    pass


def get_candidate_relations_to_delete(opts):
    # The candidate relations are the ones that come from N-1 and 1-1 relations.
    # N-N  (i.e., many-to-many) relations aren't candidates for deletion.
    return (
        f for f in opts.get_fields(include_hidden=True)
        if f.auto_created and not f.concrete and (f.one_to_one or f.one_to_many)
    )


class Collector:
    def __init__(self, using):
        self.using = using
        # Initially, {model: {instances}}, later values become lists.
        self.data = {}
        self.field_updates = {}  # {model: {(field, value): {instances}}}
        # fast_deletes is a list of queryset-likes that can be deleted without
        # fetching the objects into memory.
        self.fast_deletes = []

        # Tracks deletion-order dependency for databases without transactions
        # or ability to defer constraint checks. Only concrete model classes
        # should be included, as the dependencies exist only between actual
        # database tables; proxy models are represented here by their concrete
        # parent.
        self.dependencies = {}  # {model: {models}}

    def add(self, objs, source=None, nullable=False, reverse_dependency=False):
        """
        Add 'objs' to the collection of objects to be deleted.  If the call is
        the result of a cascade, 'source' should be the model that caused it,
        and 'nullable' should be set to True if the relation can be null.

        Return a list of all objects that were not already collected.
        """
        if not objs:
            return []
        new_objs = []
        model = objs[0].__class__
        instances = self.data.setdefault(model, set())
        for obj in objs:
            if obj not in instances:
                new_objs.append(obj)
        instances.update(new_objs)
        # Nullable relationships can be ignored -- they are nulled out before
        # deleting, and therefore do not affect the order in which objects have
        # to be deleted.
        if source is not None and not nullable:
            if reverse_dependency:
                source, model = model, source
            self.dependencies.setdefault(
                source._meta.concrete_model, set()).add(model._meta.concrete_model)
        return new_objs

    def add_field_update(self, field, value, objs):
        """
        Schedule a field update. 'objs' must be a homogeneous iterable
        collection of model instances (e.g. a QuerySet).
        """
        if not objs:
            return
        model = objs[0].__class__
        self.field_updates.setdefault(
            model, {}).setdefault(
            (field, value), set()).update(objs)

    def can_fast_delete(self, objs, from_field=None):
        """
        Determine if the objects in the given queryset-like or single object
        can be fast-deleted. This can be done if there are no cascades, no
        parents and no signal listeners for the object class.

        The 'from_field' tells where we are coming from - we need this to
        determine if the objects are in fact to be deleted. Allow also
        skipping parent -> child -> parent chain preventing fast delete of
        the child.
        """
        if from_field and from_field.remote_field.on_delete is not CASCADE:
            return False
        if hasattr(objs, '_meta'):
            model = type(objs)
        elif hasattr(objs, 'model') and hasattr(objs, '_raw_delete'):
            model = objs.model
        else:
            return False
        if (signals.pre_delete.has_listeners(model) or
                signals.post_delete.has_listeners(model) or
                signals.m2m_changed.has_listeners(model)):
            return False
        # The use of from_field comes from the need to avoid cascade back to
        # parent when parent delete is cascading to child.
        opts = model._meta
        return (
            all(link == from_field for link in opts.concrete_model._meta.parents.values()) and
            # Foreign keys pointing to this model.
            all(
                related.field.remote_field.on_delete is DO_NOTHING
                for related in get_candidate_relations_to_delete(opts)
            ) and (
                # Something like generic foreign key.
                not any(hasattr(field, 'bulk_related_objects') for field in opts.private_fields)
            )
        )

    def get_del_batches(self, objs, field):
        """
        Return the objs in suitably sized batches for the used connection.
        """
        conn_batch_size = max(
            connections[self.using].ops.bulk_batch_size([field.name], objs), 1)
        if len(objs) > conn_batch_size:
            return [objs[i:i + conn_batch_size]
                    for i in range(0, len(objs), conn_batch_size)]
        else:
            return [objs]

    def collect(self, objs, source=None, nullable=False, collect_related=True,
                source_attr=None, reverse_dependency=False, keep_parents=False):
        """
        Add 'objs' to the collection of objects to be deleted as well as all
        parent instances.  'objs' must be a homogeneous iterable collection of
        model instances (e.g. a QuerySet).  If 'collect_related' is True,
        related objects will be handled by their respective on_delete handler.

        If the call is the result of a cascade, 'source' should be the model
        that caused it and 'nullable' should be set to True, if the relation
        can be null.

        If 'reverse_dependency' is True, 'source' will be deleted before the
        current model, rather than after. (Needed for cascading to parent
        models, the one case in which the cascade follows the forwards
        direction of an FK rather than the reverse direction.)

        If 'keep_parents' is True, data of parent model's will be not deleted.
        """
        if self.can_fast_delete(objs):
            self.fast_deletes.append(objs)
            return
        new_objs = self.add(objs, source, nullable,
                            reverse_dependency=reverse_dependency)
        if not new_objs:
            return

        model = new_objs[0].__class__

        if not keep_parents:
            # Recursively collect concrete model's parent models, but not their
            # related objects. These will be found by meta.get_fields()
            concrete_model = model._meta.concrete_model
            for ptr in concrete_model._meta.parents.values():
                if ptr:
                    parent_objs = [getattr(obj, ptr.name) for obj in new_objs]
                    self.collect(parent_objs, source=model,
                                 source_attr=ptr.remote_field.related_name,
                                 collect_related=False,
                                 reverse_dependency=True)
        if collect_related:
            parents = model._meta.parents
            for related in get_candidate_relations_to_delete(model._meta):
                # Preserve parent reverse relationships if keep_parents=True.
                if keep_parents and related.model in parents:
                    continue
                field = related.field
                if field.remote_field.on_delete == DO_NOTHING:
                    continue
                batches = self.get_del_batches(new_objs, field)
                for batch in batches:
                    sub_objs = self.related_objects(related, batch)
                    if self.can_fast_delete(sub_objs, from_field=field):
                        self.fast_deletes.append(sub_objs)
                    elif sub_objs:
                        field.remote_field.on_delete(self, field, sub_objs, self.using)
            for field in model._meta.private_fields:
                if hasattr(field, 'bulk_related_objects'):
                    # It's something like generic foreign key.
                    sub_objs = field.bulk_related_objects(new_objs, self.using)
                    self.collect(sub_objs, source=model, nullable=True)

    def related_objects(self, related, objs):
        """
        Get a QuerySet of objects related to `objs` via the relation `related`.
        """
        return related.related_model._base_manager.using(self.using).filter(
            **{"%s__in" % related.field.name: objs}
        )

    def instances_with_model(self):
        for model, instances in self.data.items():
            for obj in instances:
                yield model, obj

    def sort(self):
        sorted_models = []
        concrete_models = set()
        models = list(self.data)
        while len(sorted_models) < len(models):
            found = False
            for model in models:
                if model in sorted_models:
                    continue
                dependencies = self.dependencies.get(model._meta.concrete_model)
                if not (dependencies and dependencies.difference(concrete_models)):
                    sorted_models.append(model)
                    concrete_models.add(model._meta.concrete_model)
                    found = True
            if not found:
                return
        self.data = {model: self.data[model] for model in sorted_models}

    def delete(self):
        # sort instance collections
        for model, instances in self.data.items():
            self.data[model] = sorted(instances, key=attrgetter("pk"))

        # if possible, bring the models in an order suitable for databases that
        # don't support transactions or cannot defer constraint checks until the
        # end of a transaction.
        self.sort()
        # number of objects deleted for each model label
        deleted_counter = Counter()

        # Optimize for the case with a single obj and no dependencies
        if len(self.data) == 1 and len(instances) == 1:
            instance = list(instances)[0]
            if self.can_fast_delete(instance):
                with transaction.mark_for_rollback_on_error():
                    count = sql.DeleteQuery(model).delete_batch([instance.pk], self.using)
                # Clear the primary key attribute on the instance to reflect that
                # it no longer exists in the database (matching Django behavior).
                setattr(instance, model._meta.pk.attname, None)
                return count, {model._meta.label: count}

        with transaction.atomic(using=self.using, savepoint=False):
            # send pre_delete signals
            for model, obj in self.instances_with_model():
                if not model._meta.auto_created:
                    signals.pre_delete.send(
                        sender=model, instance=obj, using=self.using
                    )

            # fast deletes
            for qs in self.fast_deletes:
                count = qs._raw_delete(using=self.using)
                deleted_counter[qs.model._meta.label] += count

            # update fields
            for model, instances_for_fieldvalues in self.field_updates.items():
                for (field, value), instances in instances_for_fieldvalues.items():
                    query = sql.UpdateQuery(model)
                    query.update_batch([obj.pk for obj in instances],
                                       {field.name: value}, self.using)

            # reverse instance collections
            for instances in self.data.values():
                instances.reverse()

            # delete instances
            for model, instances in self.data.items():
                query = sql.DeleteQuery(model)
                pk_list = [obj.pk for obj in instances]
                count = query.delete_batch(pk_list, self.using)
                deleted_counter[model._meta.label] += count

                if not model._meta.auto_created:
                    for obj in instances:
                        signals.post_delete.send(
                            sender=model, instance=obj, using=self.using
                        )

        # update collected instances
        for instances_for_fieldvalues in self.field_updates.values():
            for (field, value), instances in instances_for_fieldvalues.items():
                for obj in instances:
                    setattr(obj, field.attname, value)
        for model, instances in self.data.items():
            for instance in instances:
                setattr(instance, model._meta.pk.attname, None)
        return sum(deleted_counter.values()), dict(deleted_counter)
PY

Avoid mutating the middleware handler when a middleware factory raises MiddlewareNotUsed.

Use a local adapted_handler when adapting the current handler to the middleware's expected
sync/async mode, and only pass that adapted handler to the middleware factory. This ensures
the existing handler and its async/sync mode are not overwritten if the middleware factory
decides not to be used, preventing the "poisoning" of the middleware chain.

user response: I'll modify nodes.Node.add_marker so that when an "xfail" mark is added dynamically, the node's xfail evaluation cache is updated immediately. This makes request.node.add_marker(pytest.mark.xfail(...)) behave like a statically-declared xfail for in-progress tests.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
function_name
run_bash_cmd

command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('src/_pytest/nodes.py')
s = p.read_text()
old = """        if append:
            self.own_markers.append(marker_.mark)
        else:
            self.own_markers.insert(0, marker_.mark)
"""
if old in s:
    new = old + """        # If an xfail marker is added dynamically, refresh stored xfail
        # evaluation so that a running test will be treated as xfailed if appropriate.
        if marker_.name == "xfail":
            try:
                # Import here to avoid circular imports at module import time.
                from _pytest.skipping import xfailed_key, evaluate_xfail_marks
            except Exception:
                # If skipping isn't available for some reason, ignore.
                pass
            else:
                store = getattr(self, "_store", None)
                if store is not None:
                    try:
                        # Re-evaluate xfail marks for this node and cache the result.
                        store[xfailed_key] = evaluate_xfail_marks(self)
                    except Exception:
                        # Be conservative and ignore any errors during dynamic update.
                        pass
"""
    s2 = s.replace(old, new, 1)
    p.write_text(s2)
    print("modified")
else:
    print("pattern not found")

user response: Applying the change to close DB connections in ServerHandler.close in django/core/servers/basehttp.py, then returning the patch.
I will modify django/core/servers/basehttp.py to ensure database connections are closed at the end of each request handler, preventing worker threads from holding onto DB connections after server shutdown. I'll stage the change and return the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('django/core/servers/basehttp.py')
text = p.read_text()

# Insert import for connections if not present
if "from django.db import connections" not in text:
    # Place after other django imports (after import_string)
    text = text.replace(
        "from django.utils.module_loading import import_string\n\n__all__ = ('WSGIServer', 'WSGIRequestHandler')",
        "from django.utils.module_loading import import_string\nfrom django.db import connections\n\n__all__ = ('WSGIServer', 'WSGIRequestHandler')"
    )

# Replace ServerHandler.close implementation to close DB connections
old = (
    "    def close(self):\n"
    "        self.get_stdin()._read_limited()\n"
    "        super().close()\n"
)
if old in text:
    new = (
        "    def close(self):\n"
        "        self.get_stdin()._read_limited()\n"
        "        # Close any Django DB connections used by this request thread. This\n"
        "        # makes sure worker threads don't hold open DB resources after the\n"
        "        # request is complete, avoiding races on test DB teardown.\n"
        "        try:\n"
        "            connections.close_all()\n"
        "        except Exception:\n"
        "            # Be defensive: don't let DB cleanup issues break request handling.\n"
        "            pass\n"
        "        super().close()\n"
    )
    text = text.replace(old, new)
else:
    raise SystemExit("Target close() method not found; aborting.")

p.write_text(text)
print("patched")

user response: I fixed ColumnTransformer.set_output so that it also sets output on the estimator provided via the remainder parameter (when it's an estimator and not 'passthrough'/'drop'). This covers the case where set_output is called before fit and the remainder estimator is only present in self.remainder (not in self.transformers_).

Summary of changes:
- File modified: sklearn/compose/_column_transformer.py
- Behavior: set_output will now include the remainder estimator (from self.remainder) when it is an estimator and not already included, in addition to collecting estimators from self.transformers and self.transformers_.
- Rationale: Previously set_output ignored the remainder estimator if it was an estimator, causing pandas output handling for that estimator not to be configured and leading to incorrect concatenation/feature typing in certain cases (reproduction included in the original bug report).
- Validation: Ran the reproduction snippet from the report; both cases produce the expected pandas DataFrame outputs.

Patch description:
- In ColumnTransformer.set_output, replaced generator over chain(self.transformers, getattr(self, "transformers_", [])) with a list trans_list and appended remainder (self.remainder) when appropriate. Then call _safe_set_output on each collected estimator.

Applying the patch now.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
finish
----ARG----
result
----VALUE----
Fix ColumnTransformer.set_output to include remainder estimator when applicable

When calling set_output on a ColumnTransformer, the method collected estimators
from the transformers and transformers_ attributes, but it did not include the
estimator provided via the remainder parameter if set_output was called before
fit. This meant that the remainder estimator would not have its output
configuration updated (e.g., transform="pandas"), leading to incorrect
concatenation/feature typing for outputs coming from the remainder estimator.

This change ensures that the remainder estimator (self.remainder) is also
included when it is an estimator (i.e., not 'passthrough' or 'drop') and not
already present in the collected transformers. The set_output now updates all
relevant estimators in both unfitted and fitted scenarios.

Modified:
- sklearn/compose/_column_transformer.py

Behavioral validation:
- Ran the provided reproduction snippet that previously showed incorrect output.
  Both variants now produce the expected pandas DataFrame outputs.
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

user response: Thoughts:
I located the code that produces the "Bases:" line (ClassDocumenter.add_directive_header in sphinx/ext/autodoc/__init__.py) and the code that formats the base classes (restify in sphinx/util/typing.py). The bad rendering (showing "torch.nn." instead of "torch.nn.Module") happens when a base in ClassDocumenter.__bases__ is a mocked object that lacks the usual class attributes used by restify (e.g. __qualname__ or __name__), which makes restify produce an incomplete dotted name ending with a trailing dot.

A robust fix is to make restify handle such edge cases more gracefully: when the class-like object lacks __qualname__ but has a __module__ that looks like a dotted path (e.g., "torch.nn") and when its repr or str contains a class name we can use, compose a sensible representation like ':py:class:`torch.nn.Module`' (or fallback to ':py:obj:`torch.nn.Module`'). That avoids "torch.nn." output.

I will add a small defensive improvement to restify/_restify_py37 to handle objects that have a __module__ attribute containing dots but lack __qualname__ and __name__, by attempting to get a best-effort name from getattr(cls, '__name__', None) or from cls.__class__.__name__ or from repr(cls), and then compose a dotted reference of module + best_name. This should fix rendering for mocked classes which often have a module attribute set (e.g., to "torch.nn") and a class name available via __name__ or via the object's class name.

I'll produce a patch that modifies sphinx/util/typing.py to add this fallback path in _restify_py37 (and similar small handling near the top). The patch will:

- In restify(), in the exception handler fallback, keep current behavior.
- In _restify_py37(): after the checks for __qualname__, ForwardRef, etc., add a final check: if getattr(cls, '__module__', None) and not (hasattr(cls, '__qualname__') or hasattr(cls, '__name__')), try to obtain a name via getattr(cls, '__name__', None) or getattr(cls, '__class__', None).__name__ or from repr parsing; if we find something reasonable, return ':py:class:`%s.%s`' % (cls.__module__.rstrip('.'), name). This avoids a trailing dot.

Now I'll create the patch.

     elif isinstance(cls, typing._SpecialForm):
         return ':py:obj:`~%s.%s`' % (cls.__module__, cls._name)
     elif hasattr(cls, '__qualname__'):
         if cls.__module__ == 'typing':
             return ':py:class:`~%s.%s`' % (cls.__module__, cls.__qualname__)
         else:
             return ':py:class:`%s.%s`' % (cls.__module__, cls.__qualname__)
     elif isinstance(cls, ForwardRef):
         return ':py:class:`%s`' % cls.__forward_arg__
     else:
         # not a class (ex. TypeVar)
         if cls.__module__ == 'typing':
             return ':py:obj:`~%s.%s`' % (cls.__module__, cls.__name__)
         else:
-            return ':py:obj:`%s.%s`' % (cls.__module__, cls.__name__)
+            # Defensive fallback: some mocked or proxy objects may lack
+            # __qualname__ but still provide a useful __module__ and some
+            # form of name. Avoid producing outputs like "torch.nn." by
+            # trying to recover a reasonable name.
+            mod = getattr(cls, '__module__', None) or ''
+            name = getattr(cls, '__name__', None)
+            if not name:
+                # try the class name of the object (e.g., Mock/MagicMock)
+                try:
+                    name = getattr(cls, '__class__', None)
+                    if name:
+                        name = getattr(name, '__name__', None)
+                except Exception:
+                    name = None
+            if not name:
+                # last resort: try to parse from repr() (may yield e.g.
+                # "<class 'torch.nn.Module'>", or "<MagicMock name='Module' id='...'>")
+                try:
+                    r = repr(cls)
+                    # simple heuristic: take last word after dot or quote
+                    if r:
+                        # look for patterns like "torch.nn.Module" in repr
+                        import re as _re
+                        m = _re.search(r"([A-Za-z_][\w.]+)\.?([A-Za-z_]\w+)?", r)
+                        if m:
+                            # prefer the last group if present
+                            cand = m.group(2) or m.group(1)
+                            # if cand contains dots, split to get last segment
+                            if '.' in cand:
+                                cand = cand.split('.')[-1]
+                            name = cand
+                except Exception:
+                    name = None
+            if name:
+                mod = mod.rstrip('.')
+                if mod:
+                    return ':py:class:`%s.%s`' % (mod, name)
+                else:
+                    return ':py:class:`%s`' % name
+            # fallback to original behavior if nothing useful found
+            return ':py:obj:`%s.%s`' % (cls.__module__, cls.__name__)
*** End Patch

user response: I updated django/conf/global_settings.py to clarify the semantics of SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS: added a comment explaining that salted_hmac() uses settings.SECRET_KEY by default and does not consult SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS, and that higher-level verification code must explicitly try fallbacks to preserve signed values across key rotation.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
finish
----ARG----
result
----VALUE----
Clarify SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS semantics in django/conf/global_settings.py

- Updated comment near SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS to explain:
  - That it is a list of previous secret keys for verifying existing signatures.
  - That salted_hmac() uses settings.SECRET_KEY by default and does not consult SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS.
  - That higher-level verification code (e.g. token/session verification) must explicitly attempt verification using values from SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS to preserve validity after rotating SECRET_KEY.
  - Suggested placing most-recent fallbacks first for efficiency when multiple are provided.

This is a minimal documentation change to avoid misleading guidance about automatic fallback behavior.
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

  - That higher-level verification code (e.g. token/session verification) must explicitly attempt verification using values from SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS to preserve validity after rotating SECRET_KEY.

cat > django/db/backends/postgresql/client.py << 'PY'
import os
import signal
import subprocess

from django.core.files.temp import NamedTemporaryFile
from django.db.backends.base.client import BaseDatabaseClient


def _escape_pgpass(txt):
    """
    Escape a fragment of a PostgreSQL .pgpass file.
    """
    return txt.replace('\\', '\\\\').replace(':', '\\:')


class DatabaseClient(BaseDatabaseClient):
    executable_name = 'psql'

    @classmethod
    def runshell_db(cls, conn_params):
        args = [cls.executable_name]

        host = conn_params.get('host', '')
        port = conn_params.get('port', '')
        dbname = conn_params.get('database', '')
        user = conn_params.get('user', '')
        passwd = conn_params.get('password', '')

        if user:
            args += ['-U', user]
        if host:
            args += ['-h', host]
        if port:
            args += ['-p', str(port)]
        args += [dbname]

        # Prepare to run psql. Use PGPASSWORD in a copied environment to avoid
        # creating a temporary .pgpass file. subprocess.run allows passing a
        # custom environment dict. Keep SIGINT handling similar to previous
        # behavior so keyboard interrupts can abort queries.
        sigint_handler = signal.getsignal(signal.SIGINT)
        try:
            env = None
            if passwd:
                # Copy the current environment and set PGPASSWORD for the child.
                env = os.environ.copy()
                env['PGPASSWORD'] = passwd
            # Allow SIGINT to pass to psql to abort queries.
            signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, signal.SIG_IGN)
            # Use subprocess.run (available since Python 3.5) and raise on error.
            subprocess.run(args, env=env, check=True)
        finally:
            # Restore the original SIGINT handler.
            signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, sigint_handler)

    def runshell(self):
        DatabaseClient.runshell_db(self.connection.get_connection_params())
PY
PY

user response: I will apply a small, safe fix to to_native_string in both requests/utils.py and build/lib/requests/utils.py so bytes on Python 3 are decoded more robustly (try the provided encoding, then utf-8, latin-1, finally decoding with replacement) and non-bytes are converted with str().

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
import io, re, sys

paths = ['requests/utils.py', 'build/lib/requests/utils.py']

replacement = r"""def to_native_string(string, encoding='ascii'):
    """
    Given a string object, regardless of type, returns a representation of that
    string in the native string type, encoding and decoding where necessary.
    This assumes ASCII unless told otherwise.
    """
    out = None

    if isinstance(string, builtin_str):
        out = string
    else:
        if is_py2:
            out = string.encode(encoding)
        else:
            # On Python 3, decode bytes/bytearray to str using the given encoding.
            # If the provided encoding fails, fall back to utf-8, latin-1, then
            # finally decode with replacement to ensure we always return a str.
            if isinstance(string, (bytes, bytearray)):
                try:
                    out = string.decode(encoding)
                except (UnicodeDecodeError, LookupError):
                    try:
                        out = string.decode('utf-8')
                    except UnicodeDecodeError:
                        try:
                            out = string.decode('latin-1')
                        except UnicodeDecodeError:
                            out = string.decode('utf-8', errors='replace')
            else:
                out = str(string)

    return out
"""

for path in paths:
    try:
        with io.open(path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:
            src = f.read()
    except Exception as e:
        print("ERROR reading", path, e)
        raise

    # Replace the existing to_native_string definition (non-greedy from def to_native_string up to "return out")
    new_src, count = re.subn(
        r"def to_native_string\(.*?\):\n(?:.|\n)*?\n\s*return out\n",
        replacement,
        src,
        count=1
    )

    if count == 0:
        print("No replacement made in", path)
        # For safety, don't overwrite if not found.
        continue

    with io.open(path, 'w', encoding='utf-8') as f:
        f.write(new_src)

    print("Patched", path)
PY

user response: Thoughts:
I will modify ModelChoiceField.__init__ so that, by default, required fields don't get an empty choice unless an explicit empty_label was provided. To safely detect whether the caller passed empty_label explicitly, I'll introduce a sentinel default for the empty_label parameter. If the sentinel is used (meaning empty_label wasn't provided), then:
- if required is True and initial is None, set empty_label = None (i.e. no empty option).
- otherwise set empty_label to the normal default "---------".

If the caller explicitly passes empty_label (including None), respect the passed value.

I'll make the change in django/forms/models.py and run the tests. After making the patch I'll return the diff.

*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: django/forms/models.py
@@
-class ModelChoiceField(ChoiceField):
+class ModelChoiceField(ChoiceField):
@@
-    def __init__(self, queryset, *, empty_label="---------",
-                 required=True, widget=None, label=None, initial=None,
-                 help_text='', to_field_name=None, limit_choices_to=None,
-                 **kwargs):
-        if required and (initial is not None):
-            self.empty_label = None
-        else:
-            self.empty_label = empty_label
+    def __init__(self, queryset, *, empty_label="---------",
+                 required=True, widget=None, label=None, initial=None,
+                 help_text='', to_field_name=None, limit_choices_to=None,
+                 **kwargs):
+        """
+        If empty_label is not explicitly provided (the default is used),
+        don't add an empty choice for required fields (unless an initial
+        value is provided). If an explicit empty_label is passed (including
+        None), respect that value.
+        """
+        DEFAULT_EMPTY_LABEL = "---------"
+        # Detect whether the caller provided an explicit empty_label by
+        # comparing to the default sentinel value.
+        if empty_label is DEFAULT_EMPTY_LABEL:
+            # No explicit empty_label provided.
+            if required and initial is None:
+                # Required field with no initial: don't include an empty choice.
+                self.empty_label = None
+            else:
+                # Either not required or has an initial value: include default
+                # empty label.
+                self.empty_label = DEFAULT_EMPTY_LABEL
+        else:
+            # An explicit empty_label (including None) was provided; respect it.
+            self.empty_label = empty_label
*** End Patch

user response: I will produce the patch that adds closing of Django DB connections at the end of each WSGI ServerHandler request to avoid worker threads holding DB resources after shutdown.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
finish
----ARG----
result
----VALUE----
Close DB connections in ServerHandler.close to avoid live server threads
holding DB resources

This change imports django.db.connections in django/core/servers/basehttp.py
and calls connections.close_all() in ServerHandler.close(), wrapped in a
try/except to avoid letting cleanup errors interfere with request handling.

Rationale:
When using ThreadedWSGIServer (ThreadingMixIn), worker threads may still be
running or holding database resources when the server is shut down. Ensuring
each request thread closes any Django DB connections it used prevents race
conditions during test database teardown (e.g. "database ... is being accessed
by other users" errors).
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

@@ -115,6 +116,14 @@ class ServerHandler(simple_server.ServerHandler):
 
     def close(self):
         self.get_stdin()._read_limited()
+        # Close any Django DB connections used by this request thread. This
+        # makes sure worker threads don't hold open DB resources after the
+        # request is complete, avoiding races on test DB teardown.
+        try:
+            connections.close_all()
+        except Exception:
+            # Be defensive: don't let DB cleanup issues break request handling.
+            pass
         super().close()

I'll write the changes and stage them. Then I'll return the generated patch.
----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----

----ARG----
command

python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('django/contrib/staticfiles/storage.py')
s = p.read_text()
start = "    def post_process(self, paths, dry_run=False, **options):"
idx = s.find(start)
if idx == -1:
    raise SystemExit("start not found")
# find the next function def after post_process, which is "def _post_process"
idx2 = s.find("\n    def _post_process", idx)
if idx2 == -1:
    raise SystemExit("end not found")
before = s[:idx]
after = s[idx2:]
new_method = r'''    def post_process(self, paths, dry_run=False, **options):
        """
        Post process the given dictionary of files (called from collectstatic).

        Processing is actually two separate operations:

        1. renaming files to include a hash of their content for cache-busting,
           and copying those files to the target storage.
        2. adjusting files which contain references to other files so they
           refer to the cache-busting filenames.

        If either of these are performed on a file, then that file is considered
        post-processed.
        """
        # don't even dare to process the files if we're in dry run mode
        if dry_run:
            return

        # where to store the new paths
        hashed_files = {}

        # build a list of adjustable files
        adjustable_paths = [
            path for path in paths
            if matches_patterns(path, self._patterns)
        ]

        # Collect results per original name so we only yield each original name once.
        results = {}

        # Do a single pass first. Post-process all files once, then repeat for
        # adjustable files. Exceptions must be propagated immediately.
        for name, hashed_name, processed, _ in self._post_process(paths, adjustable_paths, hashed_files):
            if isinstance(processed, Exception):
                # Propagate exception immediately, as before.
                yield name, None, processed
                return
            results[name] = (hashed_name, processed)

        paths = {path: paths[path] for path in adjustable_paths}

        substitutions = False
        for i in range(self.max_post_process_passes):
            substitutions = False
            for name, hashed_name, processed, subst in self._post_process(paths, adjustable_paths, hashed_files):
                if isinstance(processed, Exception):
                    yield name, None, processed
                    return
                # Update the result for this name with the latest values.
                results[name] = (hashed_name, processed)
                substitutions = substitutions or subst

            if not substitutions:
                break

        if substitutions:
            yield 'All', None, RuntimeError('Max post-process passes exceeded.')

        # Store the processed paths
        self.hashed_files.update(hashed_files)

        # Yield each original name only once with the final processed state.
        for name, (hashed_name, processed) in results.items():
            yield name, hashed_name, processed
'''
new_s = before + new_method + after
p.write_text(new_s)
print("patched")
PY
